{"/service/ndnp/ct/batch_ct_kent_ver01/data/sn92051227/00415620755/1920122701/0490.xml":{"full_text":"THE TIMES: MONDAY, DECEMBER 27, 1920\nVHREB\nTY COBB SIGNING UP FOR A RECORD SALARY\nJ ill f$\n'r 't fit fl\nv-i 3 1 -ill 1 j -k.\ni i .\"'V- vZ'i&iteit\nThe popular \"Georgia Peach, one of the best known ball players, looking a little older but still strong and\nactive off and on the diamond, is shown in the picture sijning the contract which gives him a salary of 130,000 a\nyear as manager of the Detroit Tigers. Frank Navin, owner of the Detroit American League club is on the left.'\nSecretary McAdoo Launches\nReconstruction P!an\nWilliam G. McAdoo has not. It\nmenu, given up hope of becoming\nthe Democratic presidential candi\ndate. Mr. McAdoo waa a leading con\ntender for tha nomination this year,\nbut wan successfully fought by state\nleaders in New York, Indiana and Illi\nnois, who had quarreled with his father-in-law.\nMr. McAdoo gave out a statement\nrecently touching upon business con\nditions and the remedy for them,\nwhich will be read with great interest\nby people throughout the country. In\nmany respects his attitude is antago\nrlstic to the attitude of the adminis\ntration, notably in respect to the re\nvival of the wr finance corporation,\nthe taxation question and the trade\nrelations with Russia. He is also op\nposed to the policy of congress in\ngranting loans to the railroads.\nThe ex-secretary of the treasury has\ncome out as the champion of the\nfarmers. He has almost as high a\nconception of the role of the farmer\nas Emerson portrayed in his essay\ncn '-'Farming.' Mr. McAdoo dismiss\nes as irrelevant the objection to help\ning the farmers on the ground that\nthey must bear their losses a: well\nas others. He points out that farm\ning is different from every other in\ndustry, inasmuch as the farmer has\nonly one season anil is never -guaranteed\nagainst loss by the elements.\nEurope, which is undernourished,\nneeds our crops, but cannot pay for\nthem without credit. The farmer is\nIn no position to extend this credit,\nos he must have the ready cash. Mr.\nMcAdoo, therefore, favors the reviv\nal of the war finance board as the\nef ency to extend credits to Europe\nwith which to pay the farmers in\nrash for their products. He also fav\nors more liberal extension of credits\nby the federal reserve and its mem\nber banks to agriculture. So much\nfor the farmers.\nThe ex-secretary next takes up the\nrecommendation of Secretary Houston\nlor an increase the income ta.c on\nall incomes under $5000. He con\ndemns this recommendation as un\njust to people of moderate means,\nand favors, instead., a reduction in\nthe tax on moderate incomes. He\nwould refund at lrast $2,000,000,000\nof outstanding bonds as a means of\nreducing taxation. He is opposed to\nany further loana or gifts by the gov\nernment and deprecates the loan of\n$600,000,000 to the railroads and the\ncontemplated additional loan of $300,\n000.000. He wo:d immediately remove all\nrestrictions on trade with Russia. It\nmakes' no difference, he says, what\nform of government Russia chooses\nto have, he says. Trade resumption\nis essential for the world's- welfare.\nThis, he says, does not imply or car\nry with it recognition of the Soviet\ngovernment.\nFinally, Mr. McAdoo urges, as a\nmeans of economic rehabilitation the\nfixing of a definite sum as the in\ndemnity Germany has to pay. He\nfirmly believes that if the measures\npointed out by him are adopted, the\nway will be opened for the return of\nprosperity.\nThe commanding position Mr. Mc\nAdoo occupies as a former secretary\nof the treasury and director general\nof the railroads, when under govern\nment control, to say nothing of\" his\nsending as a leader in the Democrat\nic party, gives great weight to his\nviews. They are, for the most part,\nin harmony wit,h the views of busi\nness men, farmers and others. A cer\ntain piquancy is lent to them, for\ntheir divergence in some respects,\nfrom the views of the administration.\nThe ex-secretary evidently wishes the\npeople to know that he is not a \"Me,\ntoo.\"\nTo the Democratic politicians, the\ninterest in his statement lies in its\nbearing upon the next presidential\ncampaign. It will be interpreted as\nmeaning that Mr. McAdoo is definite\nly in the field.\n\"My claim\" the letter continues\n\"is supported by the Vatican and\nbacked by the French aristocracy, the\nclergy and the higher military cir\ncles. I hope that the Catholic popu\nlation of Croatia and Slovakia will be\nonly too glad to return under my\nsceptre and King Ferdinand of Ru\nmania will not refuse some territorial\nconcessions from me, who haved his\nthrone at the time when Rumania\nwas occupied by the Germans.\"\nTEXTILE MILLS\nRESUMING IN\nJAPAN\nWashington, Dec. 27. First Indi\ncations of any Improvement of world\nmarkets are coming to officials here\nfrom agents in Japan.\nReports from that country indi\ncate that the textile mills there are\nresuming operation. The financial\ncondition, however. Is such Uhat the\nassumption has been slow to date,\nthe reports declare.\nTrade Commissioner 11. A. Burtis,\nstationed in Japan by the Bureau of\nForeign and Domestic Commerce,\nnotes, however, in his reports that\nthe output of Japanese firms is in\nmany cases of poor quality and in\nnormal times would find a poor mar\nket in competition with American\nmade goods.\nConditions in Japan, however, are\nsuch, the commissioner also reports,\nthat Japanese goods are given pref\nerence in movement from tlhe manu\nfacturing centers and seaports over\nall foreign goods, and that \"if goods\ncould come without hindrance they\nwould find no difficulty in driving\nJapanese goods out of such sections\nas Manchuria.\"\nThe Japanese silk manufactur\ners, gripped by low markets for their\noutput, are directing their energies\nmore to future p-lans than present\nproduction. Frees announcements in\nJapanese newspapers tell of plans of\nthe Japanese eilk manufacturers to\njoin with Italian silk men in further\ning the development of the silk in\ndustry in China. Low labor costs\nare supposed to be the reason for\nthe proposed development of the Chi\nnese silk industry.\nJapanese packing houses are stan\ndardizing the size It tin cans and\ncomputing centals in ounces other\nreports declare. Observers here see\nin this an effort to further invade\nthe American market\nDecries Present-Day Folly\nof Chasing Amusement\nDenver, Dec. 27 A return to I\no editions prevailing during the so\ncalled \"Tark Ages' is predicted by\nMrs. Mary C. .C. Bradford, retiring\nsuperintendent of public instruction\nin Colorado.\nMrs. Bradford was defeated for re\nelection to the position in the Novem\nber Republican landslide in this\netate.\nThe movies, automobiles and other\namusements have lured the people\nnway from learning, declared Mr.'.\nBradford, a widely-known educator\noml former president of the National\nKducation association. She said an\nother \"Dark Age\" by 1950 is the in\nevitable goal of the present-day folly\nof pleasure chasing.\nMrs. Bradford's startling state\nments were made at a \"regional con\nference\" of educators at the state\ncipitol here, prasided over by P. P.\nClwtou, United States commissioner\nof education. Delegates were in. at\ntendance from Wyoming, New Mexico\nand Colorado.\n\"Unless there is an abmdonment of\nthe foily of pleasure hunting and a\nrevival of learning what kind of\nhuman will we have in another gen\neration?\" Mrs. Bradford asiked.\n\"Right now we are spending four\nt.mes as much for chewinsr gum in\ntae United Ftate as we are for edu\ncational purposes.\nwe are spending seven times as\nmuch for tobacco as for educp \"on.\nand fifteen times as much for sodas\nand soft drinks as for the inculca\ntion of learning.\nTurn Away From Books.\n\"Before the day of the movies, the\nautomobiles and the other extensive\ndiversions of today, the boys and\ngirls turned to books for amusement.\nThey became well read and acquired\nlearning.\n\"But now, they follow the line of\nleast resistance. The boys and girls\nof this age feci abused if they are not\nallowed to attend movies three times\na week. They like to joj'ride. They\nlike to be speeded around from dance\nto dance, from one social function to\nanother, from one theatre to another.\n\"There is only one thing that can\nnave us. The parents must awaken.\nThey murt realize thefr responsibility.\nThe problem of education has ceased\nto be oni for professional educators\nalone: they are doing all they can,\nbut itho parentis must co-operate.\nIn support of her claim ttiat illite\nracy is bound to grow unless there is\ninstilled into the younger generation\na desire for knowledge to replace the\nmad pursuit for pleasure, Mrs. Brad\nford declared that 20 per cent, of the\nboys drafted into the army of Uncle\nSam were unable to read and wrtto\nwhile 60 per cent, had progressed no\nfxrther than the fifth grade in their\nsohooIiPT.\nRICE CUTS\nRUIN PRODUCERS\n;ays armour\nChieago, Dec. 27 Continued price\nreduction on grain live-stock and\n\"other products of the soil' can re\nsult only in ruin for producers, .1.\nOr-den Armour, head of Armour\ncompany declared in a statement, on\nbusiness conditions Wiere today. Cur\ntailment of production ind conse\nquent scarcity and high prices. Ar\nmour warns, will follow continuation\nof the \"anti-luying hysteria.\"\n\"Price liquidation,\" said Armour,\n\"is about complete in most essential\nproduc's. The buyers strike which\nwas largely instrumental in bringing\nabout reduced prices, has been suc\ncessful. The paper profits of the war\nperiod have been wiped out as in\nflated prices returned to reasonable\nlevels. The consumers dollar has\nabout won back its pre-war buying\npower.\n\"Not all commodities h.-vve gone\nthrough the liquidation prccess; non\nperishable ones have largely resisted\nthe trend of the times, but in the long\nrun the rations prevailing between\ncommodities before the war will re\nturn. I look for additional shrlnk\nKe in s-ich thim-s as building mater\nlain and manufacturers used by rajl\nroada and public utilities but I do not\nbelieve there should be or will be\nany further reductions in the price\nof the. products of tne farm.\n\"The turn toward better business\nWill come one of these days, just as\nsuddenly and just as irresistably as\naid the present slump. The Ameri\ncan people constitute the best market\nin the world and their buying power\nis as great as it ever was.\n'The minute the public realizes\nthat prices for essentials have hit\nbottom and even gone under produc\ntion costs, buying- will be resumed\nand accumulated s;ocks in most lines\nare so lis.-rt that buying will be in\nstantly reflected in industrial activity.\n\"I believe we are right on the eve\nof the day wiien :he buying public\nwill nang out the business as usual'\nsign.\nJoseph P. Tumulty, private secre\ntary to President Wilson, will enter\nthe practice of law in Washington\nafter March 4.\nILLON'S\nllx MAIN ST.\nBridgeport\nConn.\n10 Roe St., Cecile, Paris\no MAIN ST.-.\nBridgeport,\nCorin.\n008-914 Main St., Hartford. Conn.\nZ, r i N G MILI.INEK\nTHE END OF THE YEAR BARGAINS\nAll this week we will offer values the like was never heard\nor seen before. Prices merely nominal. We want to make a\nClean Sween this week or all merehanaise.\n$3 Trimmed Hats 75c\n$4 and $5 Trimmed Hats $i.uu\n$7 Trimmed Hats i $1-98\n$10 Trimmed Hats $2.98\n$15 Trimmed Hats $4.98\n$4 Hatters' Flush Sailor Hats $1.00\n$7 Hatters' Plush Sailor Hats $1.98\n$10 Hatters' Plush Sailor Hats $3.98\n$12 to $15 Hatters' Plush Sailor Hats $4.98\n$8 to $10 Velour Hats $2.48\nReliable Fur Scarfs and Muffs at half former prices.\n$15 Black Wolf Scarfs $7.48\n$25 Blatlk Wolf Scarfs $12.48\n$35 Taupe or Black Wolf Scarfs $17.48\n$40 Black Fox Scarfs ..$19.98\n$50 Natural Skunk Scarfs $24.98\nCluldren's Fur Sets at half prices.\nSo the price cuts run on all our fur scarfs or muf